Dear Prof. Usoskin,

I am writing to share a memo extending the methodology you reviewed in Living Reviews in Solar Physics (2017). The SOL-1 pipeline integrates two cosmogenic and three observational proxies; the Gleissberg cycle (~88 yr) is detected in four of four applicable observational proxies, and a six-component harmonic model phase-fitted to the five documented Grand Solar Minima yields a Monte Carlo forecast of the next GSM at ~2126 CE (68 % CI: 2058–2206) — consistent with Steinhilber & Beer (2013) but with a narrower interval.

The substantive note (≈3 pp) is at:
https://aadmitrieff.com/research/sol1-summary-en.html
DOI: https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19638005

I would be grateful for your assessment, particularly regarding §5, Q1: whether the contribution of stochastic triggering to forecast uncertainty over a >100-year horizon can be bounded quantitatively under harmonic superposition, or requires non-linear dynamo treatment (in light of §9.1 of your 2017 review).

If the work appears suitable for posting, I would also be grateful if you could consider endorsing the arXiv submission for astro-ph.SR or physics.space-ph (code: ZUMDPL) [verify in arxiv account before sending].

Yours sincerely,
